    <function name="finalize" c:identifier="gfls_finalize" version="0.1">
      <doc xml:space="preserve"
           filename="gfls/gfls-init.c"
           line="28">Free the resources allocated by Gfls. For example it unrefs the singleton
objects.

It is not mandatory to call this function, it's just to be friendlier to
memory debugging tools. This function is meant to be called at the end of
main(). It can be called several times.</doc>
      <source-position filename="gfls/gfls-init.h" line="20"/>
      <return-value transfer-ownership="none">
        <type name="none" c:type="void"/>
      </return-value>
    </function>
    <docsection name="gfls-attribute-keys">
      <doc xml:space="preserve"
           filename="gfls/gfls-attribute-keys.c"
           line="7">#GflsAttributeKeys is a small utility to build a list of #GFile attribute
keys. The result is a single string to pass as an argument to a function like
g_file_query_info().

It is useful for doing only a single query with a list of keys coming from
different parts of the program. To take an example, Gfls might have its own
list of keys to query, but it is desirable to ask the application for
additional keys.</doc>
    </docsection>
    <docsection name="gfls-input-stream">
      <doc xml:space="preserve"
           filename="gfls/gfls-input-stream.c"
           line="7">Additional functions for #GInputStream.</doc>
    </docsection>
    <docsection name="gfls-loader-basic">
      <doc xml:space="preserve"
           filename="gfls/gfls-loader-basic.c"
           line="10">Basic file loader that validates input for GtkTextView purposes:
- Must not exceed a certain size (because all the content of a GtkTextBuffer
  is stored in memory).
- Must be valid UTF-8 already (GTK in general accepts only UTF-8 only
  strings).
- Must not contain very long lines (not well supported by the GtkTextView
  widget, there can be performance problems and freezes).

So:
- No character encoding auto-detection and/or conversion.
- No workarounds for problems found, just return an error without the
  possibility to re-configure the loading.

But this basic file loader offers a convenient API for the above: #GFile
loading with the intention to put its content into a GtkTextBuffer.</doc>
    </docsection>
    <docsection name="gfls-loader-config">
      <doc xml:space="preserve"
           filename="gfls/gfls-loader-config.c"
           line="7">#GflsLoaderConfig is an interface that classes implement to store a loader
configuration.

Currently it is an empty interface, also called a “marker interface”.</doc>
    </docsection>
    <docsection name="gfls-unsaved-document-titles">
      <doc xml:space="preserve"
           filename="gfls/gfls-unsaved-document-titles.c"
           line="9">#GflsUnsavedDocumentTitles is used to give titles to unsaved documents, such
as "Unsaved Document N" with 'N' replaced by a number.

This is for new documents that have never been saved before and reside in
memory only. These documents have not yet an associated #GFile.

Do not confuse it with documents with unsaved &lt;emphasis&gt;changes&lt;/emphasis&gt;.</doc>
    </docsection>
    <docsection name="gfls-utf8">
      <doc xml:space="preserve"
           filename="gfls/gfls-utf8.c"
           line="7">Additional functions for UTF-8 strings, to complement what is provided by
GLib.</doc>
    </docsection>
    <function name="init" c:identifier="gfls_init" version="0.1">
      <doc xml:space="preserve"
           filename="gfls/gfls-init.c"
           line="13">Initializes the Gfls library (e.g. for the internationalization).

This function can be called several times, but is meant to be called at the
beginning of main(), before any other Gfls function call.</doc>
      <source-position filename="gfls/gfls-init.h" line="17"/>
      <return-value transfer-ownership="none">
        <type name="none" c:type="void"/>
      </return-value>
    </function>
    <function name="input_stream_read_async"
              c:identifier="gfls_input_stream_read_async"
              version="0.1">
      <doc xml:space="preserve"
           filename="gfls/gfls-input-stream.c"
           line="261">This function starts a read operation on @input_stream. It is meant to be
used as the only read operation on @input_stream, to get a #GBytes as a
result, with @max_size as the provided maximum number of bytes to read.

@expected_size is typically a #GFile size as returned by
g_file_info_get_size(). But note that in that case, the returned #GBytes may
contain a different number of bytes than what was expected (the
TOC/TOU problem: time of check to time of use). @expected_size is used as an
indication to how much memory to allocate initially.

See the #GAsyncResult documentation to know how to use this function.</doc>
      <source-position filename="gfls/gfls-input-stream.h" line="17"/>
      <return-value transfer-ownership="none">
        <type name="none" c:type="void"/>
      </return-value>
      <parameters>
        <parameter name="input_stream" transfer-ownership="none">
          <doc xml:space="preserve"
               filename="gfls/gfls-input-stream.c"
               line="263">a #GInputStream.</doc>
          <type name="Gio.InputStream" c:type="GInputStream*"/>
        </parameter>
        <parameter name="expected_size" transfer-ownership="none">
          <doc xml:space="preserve"
               filename="gfls/gfls-input-stream.c"
               line="264">the expected number of bytes contained in @input_stream.</doc>
          <type name="gsize" c:type="gsize"/>
        </parameter>
        <parameter name="max_size" transfer-ownership="none">
          <doc xml:space="preserve"
               filename="gfls/gfls-input-stream.c"
               line="265">the maximum number of bytes to read.</doc>
          <type name="gsize" c:type="gsize"/>
        </parameter>
        <parameter name="io_priority" transfer-ownership="none">
          <doc xml:space="preserve"
               filename="gfls/gfls-input-stream.c"
               line="266">the I/O priority of the request. E.g. %G_PRIORITY_LOW,
  %G_PRIORITY_DEFAULT or %G_PRIORITY_HIGH.</doc>
          <type name="gint" c:type="gint"/>
        </parameter>
        <parameter name="cancellable"
                   transfer-ownership="none"
                   nullable="1"
                   allow-none="1">
          <doc xml:space="preserve"
               filename="gfls/gfls-input-stream.c"
               line="268">optional #GCancellable object, %NULL to ignore.</doc>
          <type name="Gio.Cancellable" c:type="GCancellable*"/>
        </parameter>
        <parameter name="callback"
                   transfer-ownership="none"
                   nullable="1"
                   allow-none="1"
                   scope="async"
                   closure="6">
          <doc xml:space="preserve"
               filename="gfls/gfls-input-stream.c"
               line="269">a #GAsyncReadyCallback to call when the operation
  is finished.</doc>
          <type name="Gio.AsyncReadyCallback" c:type="GAsyncReadyCallback"/>
        </parameter>
        <parameter name="user_data"
                   transfer-ownership="none"
                   nullable="1"
                   allow-none="1">
          <doc xml:space="preserve"
               filename="gfls/gfls-input-stream.c"
               line="271">user data to pass to @callback.</doc>
          <type name="gpointer" c:type="gpointer"/>
        </parameter>
      </parameters>
    </function>
    <function name="input_stream_read_finish"
              c:identifier="gfls_input_stream_read_finish"
              version="0.1"
              throws="1">
      <doc xml:space="preserve"
           filename="gfls/gfls-input-stream.c"
           line="311">Finishes an operation started with gfls_input_stream_read_async().

If @is_truncated is set to %TRUE, it is not an error (@error is not set), and
a #GBytes is returned. However, since gfls_input_stream_read_async() is meant
to be used as the only read operation on @input_stream, it is an undefined
behavior if you try to read more content from @input_stream.

The data contained in the resulting #GBytes is always zero-terminated, but
this is not included in the #GBytes length. The resulting #GBytes should be
freed with g_bytes_unref() when no longer in use.</doc>
      <source-position filename="gfls/gfls-input-stream.h" line="26"/>
      <return-value transfer-ownership="full">
        <doc xml:space="preserve"
             filename="gfls/gfls-input-stream.c"
             line="330">a #GBytes, or %NULL on error.</doc>
        <type name="GLib.Bytes" c:type="GBytes*"/>
      </return-value>
      <parameters>
        <parameter name="input_stream" transfer-ownership="none">
          <doc xml:space="preserve"
               filename="gfls/gfls-input-stream.c"
               line="313">a #GInputStream.</doc>
          <type name="Gio.InputStream" c:type="GInputStream*"/>
        </parameter>
        <parameter name="result" transfer-ownership="none">
          <doc xml:space="preserve"
               filename="gfls/gfls-input-stream.c"
               line="314">a #GAsyncResult.</doc>
          <type name="Gio.AsyncResult" c:type="GAsyncResult*"/>
        </parameter>
        <parameter name="is_truncated" transfer-ownership="none">
          <doc xml:space="preserve"
               filename="gfls/gfls-input-stream.c"
               line="315">will be set to %TRUE if the @input_stream contains more data
  to be read, but the maximum number of bytes to read has been reached.</doc>
          <type name="gboolean" c:type="gboolean*"/>
        </parameter>
      </parameters>
    </function>
    <function name="loader_basic_load_async"
              c:identifier="gfls_loader_basic_load_async"
              version="0.1">
      <doc xml:space="preserve"
           filename="gfls/gfls-loader-basic.c"
           line="263">Starts a basic file loading operation.

If the @file content is not a valid UTF-8 string, or if the @max_size or
@max_n_bytes_per_line conditions are not satisfied, an error will be returned
without the file content.

See the #GAsyncResult documentation to know how to use this function.</doc>
      <source-position filename="gfls/gfls-loader-basic.h" line="17"/>
      <return-value transfer-ownership="none">
        <type name="none" c:type="void"/>
      </return-value>
      <parameters>
        <parameter name="file" transfer-ownership="none">
          <doc xml:space="preserve"
               filename="gfls/gfls-loader-basic.c"
               line="265">a #GFile.</doc>
          <type name="Gio.File" c:type="GFile*"/>
        </parameter>
        <parameter name="max_size" transfer-ownership="none">
          <doc xml:space="preserve"
               filename="gfls/gfls-loader-basic.c"
               line="266">the maximum allowed number of bytes in total.</doc>
          <type name="gsize" c:type="gsize"/>
        </parameter>
        <parameter name="max_n_bytes_per_line" transfer-ownership="none">
          <doc xml:space="preserve"
               filename="gfls/gfls-loader-basic.c"
               line="267">the maximum allowed number of bytes per line, as per
  gfls_utf8_find_very_long_line().</doc>
          <type name="guint" c:type="guint"/>
        </parameter>
        <parameter name="io_priority" transfer-ownership="none">
          <doc xml:space="preserve"
               filename="gfls/gfls-loader-basic.c"
               line="269">the I/O priority of the request. E.g. %G_PRIORITY_LOW,
  %G_PRIORITY_DEFAULT or %G_PRIORITY_HIGH.</doc>
          <type name="gint" c:type="gint"/>
        </parameter>
        <parameter name="cancellable"
                   transfer-ownership="none"
                   nullable="1"
                   allow-none="1">
          <doc xml:space="preserve"
               filename="gfls/gfls-loader-basic.c"
               line="271">optional #GCancellable object, %NULL to ignore.</doc>
          <type name="Gio.Cancellable" c:type="GCancellable*"/>
        </parameter>
        <parameter name="callback"
                   transfer-ownership="none"
                   nullable="1"
                   allow-none="1"
                   scope="async"
                   closure="6">
          <doc xml:space="preserve"
               filename="gfls/gfls-loader-basic.c"
               line="272">a #GAsyncReadyCallback to call when the operation
  is finished.</doc>
          <type name="Gio.AsyncReadyCallback" c:type="GAsyncReadyCallback"/>
        </parameter>
        <parameter name="user_data"
                   transfer-ownership="none"
                   nullable="1"
                   allow-none="1">
          <doc xml:space="preserve"
               filename="gfls/gfls-loader-basic.c"
               line="274">user data to pass to @callback.</doc>
          <type name="gpointer" c:type="gpointer"/>
        </parameter>
      </parameters>
    </function>
    <function name="loader_basic_load_finish"
              c:identifier="gfls_loader_basic_load_finish"
              version="0.1"
              throws="1">
      <doc xml:space="preserve"
           filename="gfls/gfls-loader-basic.c"
           line="310">Finishes an operation started with gfls_loader_basic_load_async().

If everything went well, a #GBytes with the #GFile content (unmodified) is
returned. It is guaranteed to be a valid UTF-8 string.

Otherwise an error is returned. The %GFLS_LOADER_ERROR domain is used, among
others.

The data contained in the resulting #GBytes is always zero-terminated, but
this is not included in the #GBytes length. The resulting #GBytes should be
freed with g_bytes_unref() when no longer in use.</doc>
      <source-position filename="gfls/gfls-loader-basic.h" line="26"/>
      <return-value transfer-ownership="full">
        <doc xml:space="preserve"
             filename="gfls/gfls-loader-basic.c"
             line="328">a #GBytes, or %NULL on error.</doc>
        <type name="GLib.Bytes" c:type="GBytes*"/>
      </return-value>
      <parameters>
        <parameter name="file" transfer-ownership="none">
          <doc xml:space="preserve"
               filename="gfls/gfls-loader-basic.c"
               line="312">a #GFile.</doc>
          <type name="Gio.File" c:type="GFile*"/>
        </parameter>
        <parameter name="result" transfer-ownership="none">
          <doc xml:space="preserve"
               filename="gfls/gfls-loader-basic.c"
               line="313">a #GAsyncResult.</doc>
          <type name="Gio.AsyncResult" c:type="GAsyncResult*"/>
        </parameter>
      </parameters>
    </function>
    <function name="loader_error_quark"
              c:identifier="gfls_loader_error_quark"
              moved-to="LoaderError.quark">
      <return-value transfer-ownership="none">
        <type name="GLib.Quark" c:type="GQuark"/>
      </return-value>
    </function>
    <function name="utf8_find_very_long_line"
              c:identifier="gfls_utf8_find_very_long_line"
              version="0.3">
      <doc xml:space="preserve"
           filename="gfls/gfls-utf8.c"
           line="16">Finds if a line in @str exceeds @max_n_bytes_per_line.

For performance reasons, @str is not checked whether it is a valid UTF-8
string. So you must call for example g_utf8_validate() beforehand.</doc>
      <source-position filename="gfls/gfls-utf8.h" line="17"/>
      <return-value transfer-ownership="none">
        <doc xml:space="preserve"
             filename="gfls/gfls-utf8.c"
             line="27">a pointer to the beginning of the first very long line found, or
  %NULL if not found.</doc>
        <type name="utf8" c:type="const gchar*"/>
      </return-value>
      <parameters>
        <parameter name="str" transfer-ownership="none">
          <doc xml:space="preserve"
               filename="gfls/gfls-utf8.c"
               line="18">a UTF-8 nul-terminated string.</doc>
          <type name="utf8" c:type="const gchar*"/>
        </parameter>
        <parameter name="max_n_bytes_per_line" transfer-ownership="none">
          <doc xml:space="preserve"
               filename="gfls/gfls-utf8.c"
               line="19">the maximum number of bytes per line, without counting
  the newline character(s).</doc>
          <type name="guint" c:type="guint"/>
        </parameter>
      </parameters>
    </function>
  </namespace>
